as for my contribution, this process for face swaps is user friendly and can be done on your phone:

1. take a good porn image to work with and throw it in faceapp. as OP said, you can use a surprisingly wide variety of images but you'll get the best results with a clearly visible face with similar skin tone and face shape. use the swap face tool and you'll be 90% of the way there. save the image
2. take your faceapp image and crop out the face using an editor. throw it in reface. reface typically improves the faceapp face with more accurate features
3. replace the cropped, refaced image over the original faceapp image. at this point, it's helpful to throw the image in remini pro or some other AI image enhancer. once you do that, you've got a clear and good swap.

obviously you'll want to play around and make adjustments--for example you can use other tools on faceapp to help get a more accurate image (e.g. hair style transfer, hair color transfer, reshape tools) before exporting it to reface--but in general the process above is a good starting point to get into faceswaps

There are plenty of tutorials on YouTube on how to run SD on Runpod or Vast ai (cloud GPU services)
This is my process on Vast, perhaps it will help you get started.

1. First, upload your favorite Stable Diffusion model to Google Drive.
2. Set the privacy setting of the file to "Share with Anyone with a Link"
3. Extract the unique ID from that link and swap it out with the XXXX's in the code below

Setting up with Vast:

4. Add $5.00 to your Vast account.
5. Click on "Create" on the left panel. Select "Edit IMAGE & Configuration"
6. Select "run a Jupyter-python notebook". Checkmark Jupyter Lab interface below. Hit "Select and Save".
**If you want to run HTTPS, you'll need to add a certificate. See the Tutorials on Vast's FAQ
7. Set "Disk Space to Allocate" to ~33 GB's of storage space.
8. Filter out GPU models with the drop down above, I use an RTX 3090
9. Set # of GPU's to 1X.
10. Now you're ready to RENT out a GPU. Look for an instance priced around $0.300 / HR with a download speed over 100 MBPS
11. Select RENT
******* After you wrap up, Always STOP and DELETE your instance *****
If you leave it undeleted, it will incur a daily storage cost. It's unlikely that same instance will be available to use when you come back.
The setup takes 20 minutes and you can easily set up a new session every time you want to use Stable Diffusion.

Opening up your rented instance:

12. Click on Instances in the left panel
13. Hit OPEN. You might have to wait a few minutes while its setting up.
14. Click on "Python 3" under Notebook, on the very top.

>>18713982
Work in sections. I use the official inpainting 1.5, all other models are sorta trash for fakes imo (or I'm too stupid to use them). I normally start with a high padding 512x512px 12-20 steps 0.95 denoising on first pass. Final pass uses a slightly expanded mask and low padding with 704x704px, 150 steps, and 0.1 denoising. If an image doesn't like to cooperate just right I do a few (or a lot of) intermediate passes with 512x512px, 20-35steps, 0.2-0.5 denoising.

Biggest other tips:
1. Use the padding to give the ai enough context to do what you want it to.
2. Look for "Apply color correction to img2img results to match original colors." in settings. Keep it on unless it gives you wierd artifacting, then turn it off just for that pass. Keeps the area worked on from getting progressively redder.
3. Keep prompts simple. Normally I just use "naked" for 90% of passes. Add to the prompt if the AI doesn't cooperate.
4. Final pass is for fixing skin texture mostly. Even if it doesn't look quite good yet, it can be a good idea to do a "final" but then go back in to any problem areas.
